1)Remote Repository
-----------------------
    GitHub :    
    ---->One example of remote repository hosting serivce
    ---->GitHub is a web-based platform that provides hosting for Git repositories, allowing         -developers to collaborate on projects, manage code, and track changes. It offers features such as ---pull requests, issues tracking, and project management tools, making it a popular choice for open--source and private projects alike.    

2)Local Reposiory
-----------------------
    Local Repository:
---> Local Repository is a copy of the remote repository that exists on your computer. It allows you to work on the project offline and make changes to the code. You can commit your changes to the local repository, and later push those changes to the remote repository on GitHub when you're ready to share them with others. The local repository is where you do your development work before syncing it with the remote repository.

4)Working Directory
-----------------------
    Working Directory:
--->The working directory is the actual folder on your computer where you have the project files. It is where you make changes to the code, add new files, and delete existing ones. The working directory reflects the current state of your project, and any changes you make here can be staged and committed to the local repository before being pushed to the remote repository on GitHub.

3)Staging Area
-----------------------
    Staging Area:
--->The staging area, also known as the index, is an intermediate area where you can prepare your changes before committing them to the local repository. When you make changes to your files in the working directory, you can use the `git add` command to move those changes to the staging area. This allows you to review and organize your changes before finalizing them with a commit. Once you're satisfied with the staged changes, you can use the `git commit` command to save them to the local repository.

git init--->To Initialize the new repository
git status---> To check the status of pushing changes into remote repository
git add .--->To add all the changes into staging area 
git add filename ----> for saving particular files into the staging area
git commit -m "message" ---> To commit the changes into local repository
git branch ---> for the current branch
git push origin main ---> To push the changes into remote repository


