-----------------BRANCHS----------------------
Branch:
--->A branch in Git is a separate line of development that allows you to work on different features or bug fixes without affecting the main codebase. It enables multiple developers to collaborate on the same project simultaneously by creating their own branches for specific tasks. Branches can be merged back into the main branch (often called "main" or "master") once the work is complete and tested, allowing for a more organized and efficient workflow.

    ==>git checkout -b "copy1" --> 
    ==>git checkout "copy1"
    ==>git branch "copy2"

-----------------Issues and PRs----------------------
Issues:
--->Issues in GitHub are a way to track tasks, enhancements, and bugs for your projects. They provide a platform for developers and users to report problems, suggest features, and discuss improvements. Each issue can be assigned to specific team members, labeled for organization, and tracked through its lifecycle until it is resolved.
Pull Requests (PRs):
--->Pull Requests (PRs) in GitHub are a way to propose changes to a codebase. When a developer wants to contribute to a project, they can create a pull request to merge their changes from a feature branch into the main branch. PRs allow for code review, discussion, and collaboration before the changes are integrated into the main codebase, ensuring that the quality of the code is maintained and that any potential issues are addressed.

